				\begin{document}$$ {\chi}_3^2 $$\end{document}χ32 = 3.7, p = 0.296), or between aspirin and placebo (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\chi}_3^2 $$\end{document}χ32 = 2.5, p = 0.468—Fig. 2). A priori comparison of change from baseline to week 12 showed − 4.2 (95% CI [− 9.1, 0.6]) additional improvement (i.e. change from baseline to week 12) in rosuvastatin, compared with placebo; however, the difference was not statistically significant (p = 0.089). There was no significant separation between aspirin and placebo (p = 0.433) on the MADRS. The rosuvastatin vs. aspirin group comparison was statistically significant across all post-baseline time points (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
